id: world-plan-lightweight-mode
title: WorldPlan.lightweight=True skips LLM-driven entity generation
scope: feature
owners: [@TODO]
paths:
  - volnix/engines/world_compiler/plan.py
  - volnix/engines/world_compiler/engine.py
surfaces:
  - WorldPlan.lightweight
  - WorldCompilerEngine.generate_world (lightweight branch)
dependencies: [workflow]

intent:
  Volnix's ``WorldCompilerEngine.generate_world`` runs an LLM-driven
  multi-step pipeline (compile NL policy triggers, generate entities
  per section, expand actor personalities per role, validate +
  repair, inject seeds). For chat-only worlds — where the consumer
  has already supplied complete actor specs and there are no
  entities, no policies, no seeds, and no services to populate —
  this pipeline is dead overhead. Every step burns LLM budget +
  multi-second latency for output the consumer doesn't need. This
  change adds a ``WorldPlan.lightweight: bool = False`` opt-in flag
  that short-circuits ``generate_world`` to a pass-through path:
  validate the actor_specs the consumer supplied, then return a
  result dict with the same shape downstream code expects but with
  empty/pass-through values. No LLM calls. <100ms compile.

behaviors:
  # Plan field
  - ``WorldPlan`` MUST gain a ``lightweight: bool = False`` field.
    Default ``False`` preserves every existing call site
    byte-identical. Frozen-Pydantic discipline unchanged.
  - The field MUST be plain ``bool`` (not ``Literal``, not ``Enum``).
    "Is this a lightweight world" is a binary, no future enum
    members anticipated.
  - The field MUST appear in the documented WorldPlan ordering
    next to the other behavior-mode fields (``behavior``,
    ``fidelity``, ``mode``) — it's a peer mode flag.

  # Compiler short-circuit
  - When ``plan.lightweight is True``, ``generate_world(plan)``
    MUST return immediately after ``actor_specs`` validation, with
    a result dict of the shape downstream callers expect.
    Specifically:
    - ``result["entities"] = {}`` (empty dict, not absent)
    - ``result["actors"] = list[ActorDefinition]`` produced from
      ``plan.actor_specs`` via the existing
      ``CompilerPersonalityGenerator.expand_actor_structure(...)``
      call WITHOUT the LLM personality-batch generation step. Actor
      personality is taken from whatever the consumer included in
      ``actor_specs`` (typically via
      ``CharacterDefinition.to_actor_spec()``). If a personality
      field is missing on a passed actor_spec, the actor lands with
      ``personality=None`` rather than failing.
    - ``result["validation_sections"] = {}``
    - ``result["retry_counts"] = {}``
    - ``result["applied_seed_invariants"] = {}``
    - any other keys downstream callers look up under
      ``.get(key, {})`` MUST return an empty container of the
      expected type
  - The lightweight branch MUST NOT require ``self._llm_router``.
    The current ``if not self._llm_router: raise CompilerError``
    guard at the top of ``generate_world`` MUST be moved INSIDE the
    non-lightweight path, so a lightweight compile succeeds even
    when no LLM provider is configured.
  - The lightweight branch MUST log one ``logger.info`` line
    naming the world and the lightweight mode (``"Generating
    lightweight world '%s' (no entities, no LLM calls)"``).
  - The lightweight branch MUST NOT call:
    - ``_compile_policy_triggers`` (skips NL policy compilation)
    - ``WorldDataGenerator.iter_generation_specs`` /
      ``_generate_validated_entity_section`` (skips entity gen)
    - ``CompilerPersonalityGenerator``'s LLM-driven role-batch
      personality generation (skips
      ``_generate_validated_role_batch``)
    - ``_repair_world_entity_sections`` (nothing to repair)
    - ``CompilerSeedProcessor.process_seeds`` (no seeds to inject)
  - Plan-level ``actor_specs`` MUST still be validated for
    structural correctness (each entry has ``id``, ``role``, etc.).
    Validation reuses whatever the existing
    ``expand_actor_structure`` does today; lightweight does not
    introduce new validation, only skips the LLM-augmented bits.

  # App-facade pass-through
  - ``VolnixApp.create_world(plan)`` MUST work unchanged when
    ``plan.lightweight is True``. The world manager still creates
    the world directory + state.db, the state engine still
    reconfigures, generation.json still gets written. The
    ``total_entities`` count in metadata MUST be 0 for a
    lightweight world; ``actor_count`` reflects ``len(actors)``.

  # Phase 0 regression oracle
  - ``WorldPlan(...)`` calls without an explicit ``lightweight``
    argument MUST be byte-identical to today (default ``False`` →
    existing path). Phase 0 oracle output MUST remain
    byte-identical.

non-goals:
  - No new public method on ``VolnixApp`` (no ``create_chat_world``
    parallel API). The flag rides on the existing plan, the
    existing ``create_world`` call works unchanged.
  - No deprecation of the heavy path. Heavy compilation remains
    the default and the recommended path for worlds with real
    entities, policies, services, or LLM-driven personalities.
  - No new dependency injection for the lightweight branch. It
    consumes the same ``CompilerPersonalityGenerator`` /
    ``CompilerWorldValidator`` infrastructure but skips the
    LLM-call branches inside them.
  - No change to ``compile_from_yaml`` / ``compile_from_nl``.
    Those produce ``WorldPlan`` instances; whether the resulting
    plan has ``lightweight=True`` is the consumer's decision at
    plan-construction time. (Optional follow-up TNL: a YAML-side
    ``lightweight: true`` shorthand. Not in this scope.)
  - No interaction with ``WorldPlan.characters`` auto-dereference
    (Gap 4) — that's a separate TNL. If a lightweight world uses
    the ``characters`` field, it still needs the consumer to have
    dereferenced into ``actor_specs`` until Gap 4 ships.
  - No CLI surface change. Library consumers set the flag
    programmatically via ``WorldPlan(..., lightweight=True)`` or
    ``ConfigBuilder``-style construction.

rationale:
  Two design options were on the table: (a) a ``lightweight: bool``
  flag on ``WorldPlan``, or (b) a separate
  ``VolnixApp.create_chat_world(plan)`` entry point. Option (a) was
  chosen because:
  - The "is this a chat-only world" question is a property of the
    world definition, not a separate operation. Plan-driven matches
    the existing flag pattern (``behavior``, ``fidelity``, ``mode``
    are all plan-level mode flags).
  - Single API surface means downstream consumers don't need to
    branch their call site between two entry points.
  - The flag travels with the plan into ``world_manager``,
    metadata, generation.json, and any future audit/replay path —
    "this world was generated as lightweight" is preserved
    structurally rather than implied by the entry point used.
  - Adding a parallel entry point would create a maintenance burden
    every time the heavy path's signature evolves.

  Skipping the LLM-router-required guard in the lightweight branch
  is intentional. It enables fully offline / no-API-key consumers
  (test harnesses, CI without provider creds, downstream products
  that ship without LLM defaults) to compile lightweight worlds for
  the chat-only workflow. Consumers who later decide they need a
  heavyweight world get the existing loud failure.
